# Plan: Add `mistral-instruct-v3` Specialized Chat Template Handler

## Context

The llama.cpp codebase has a two-tier chat template system:
- **Legacy** (`src/llama-chat.cpp`): C++ enum-based templates using heuristic string detection, mapped to a `llm_chat_template` enum in `src/llama-chat.h`.
- **Modern specialized** (`common/chat.cpp`): PEG-parser-based handlers registered via the `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` function. These are identified by pattern-matching the raw Jinja template source and return full `common_chat_params` (prompt + PEG parser + optional grammar).

The existing Ministral 3 handler already covers Mistral templates that use `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]...[/SYSTEM_PROMPT]` for system messages (the "v7" format). The Mistral Instruct v0.3 format (used by models like Mistral Nemo) instead **prepends** system content directly into the first user turn, wrapping it with `[INST]...[/INST]`, and appends `</s>` after assistant turns. This format is not yet handled by a specialized PEG-based handler, so it falls through to the generic autoparser.

This plan adds a new specialized handler for this format without touching any existing code.

---

## Critical Files

| File | Role |
|------|------|
| `common/chat.cpp` | **Only file to modify** — contains all specialized handlers and `common_chat_try_specialized_template()` |
| `common/chat.h` | Data structures (`common_chat_params`, `common_chat_templates_inputs`) — read-only reference |
| `src/llama-chat.h` | Enum definitions — **do not modify** (per task constraints) |
| `src/llama-chat.cpp` | Legacy detection + name map — **do not modify** |
| `models/templates/mistralai-Mistral-Nemo-Instruct-2407.jinja` | Reference template for the target format |

---

## Mistral Instruct v0.3 Template Format (from Mistral Nemo Jinja)

- **System**: extracted from messages array, prepended to first user turn — NOT wrapped in `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`
- **User**: `[INST]{content}[/INST]` (no spaces, Tekken-style)
- **First user with system**: `[INST]{system_message}\n\n{user_content}[/INST]`
- **Assistant**: `{content}</s>` (eos_token appended)
- **Tool definitions**: `[AVAILABLE_TOOLS][...][/AVAILABLE_TOOLS]` (prepended to last user turn)
- **Tool calls**: `[TOOL_CALLS][{"name":"func","arguments":{...},"id":"XXXXXXXXX"}]</s>`

**Key distinguisher from Ministral 3**: Ministral 3 templates have `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` AND `[TOOL_CALLS]` AND `[ARGS]`. The Nemo-style templates have `[INST]` and `[TOOL_CALLS]` but **no** `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` and **no** `[ARGS]`.

---

## Implementation — Only `common/chat.cpp`

### Step 1: Add the handler function

Insert a new `static` function **immediately before** `common_chat_try_specialized_template` (around line 1622, after the closing `}` of the helper namespace).

**Function signature** (follows the exact same pattern as all other handlers):
```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &              tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params &     inputs);
```

**Function body** (modelled after `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` for the simple case, with tool-call handling modelled after `common_chat_params_init_ministral_3` but adapted for the JSON-array tool call format):

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    // Apply the Jinja template as-is; system message prepending is
    // handled by the Jinja template itself (prepended to first [INST] turn).
    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;
    data.preserved_tokens  = {
        "[INST]", "[/INST]",
        "[TOOL_CALLS]",
        "[AVAILABLE_TOOLS]", "[/AVAILABLE_TOOLS]",
    };

    auto has_tools       = inputs.tools.is_array() && !inputs.tools.empty();
    auto include_grammar = has_tools && inputs.tool_choice != COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE;

    // Tool calls are emitted as a JSON array:
    //   [TOOL_CALLS][{"name":"func","arguments":{...},"id":"XXXXXXXXX"}]
    const std::string TOOL_CALLS_START = "[TOOL_CALLS]";

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        if (!has_tools || inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_NONE) {
            include_grammar = false;
            return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
        }

        // Build per-tool parsing rules.
        // Each element: {"name":"func_name","arguments":{...},"id":"XXXXXXXXX"}
        auto tool_choice = p.choice();
        foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
            const auto & function = tool.at("function");
            std::string  name     = function.at("name");
            const auto & schema   = function.at("parameters");

            auto tool_name = p.json_member("name", "\"" + p.tool_name(p.literal(name)) + "\"");
            auto tool_args = p.json_member("arguments",
                                 p.tool_args(p.schema(p.json(), "tool-" + name + "-schema", schema)));
            auto tool_open = p.tool_open(p.literal("{") << tool_name);

            // Match the full object including the trailing "id" field.
            tool_choice |= p.rule("tool-" + name,
                                  tool_open << "," << tool_args << "," << p.json_member("id", p.json()) << "}");
        });

        auto min_calls  = inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_REQUIRED ? 1 : 0;
        auto max_calls  = inputs.parallel_tool_calls ? -1 : 1;
        // The JSON array wrapper: [TOOL_CALLS][{tool},{tool},...]
        auto tool_calls = p.trigger_rule("tool-call",
            p.literal(TOOL_CALLS_START + "[") +
            p.repeat(tool_choice, min_calls, max_calls) +
            p.literal("]"));

        auto content = p.content(p.until(TOOL_CALLS_START));
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + content + tool_calls;
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    if (include_grammar) {
        data.grammar_lazy = inputs.tool_choice == COMMON_CHAT_TOOL_CHOICE_AUTO;
        data.grammar = build_grammar([&](const common_grammar_builder & builder) {
            foreach_function(inputs.tools, [&](const json & tool) {
                const auto & function = tool.at("function");
                auto         schema   = function.at("parameters");
                builder.resolve_refs(schema);
            });
            parser.build_grammar(builder, data.grammar_lazy);
        });
        data.grammar_triggers = {
            { COMMON_GRAMMAR_TRIGGER_TYPE_WORD, TOOL_CALLS_START }
        };
    }

    return data;
}
```

**Reused patterns / utilities** (all from `common/chat.cpp`):
- `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs)` — applies Jinja template (overload at line ~821)
- `build_chat_peg_parser(...)` — PEG builder factory
- `foreach_function(inputs.tools, ...)` — iterates tool definitions
- `build_grammar(...)` — grammar builder factory
- `p.json_member(...)`, `p.tool_name(...)`, `p.tool_open(...)`, `p.tool_args(...)`, `p.schema(...)`, `p.repeat(...)`, `p.choice()`, `p.content(...)`, `p.until(...)`, `p.rest()`, `p.literal(...)` — PEG builder API used identically to other handlers

---

### Step 2: Register in `common_chat_try_specialized_template`

Add one `if` block **after** the existing Ministral 3 check (ends at line 1644) and **before** the GPT-OSS check.

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v3 — uses [INST]/[/INST] without the [SYSTEM_PROMPT] wrapper.
// Distinguishes from Ministral/Magistral 3 by the absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT].
// Also excludes Llama 2 variants that use <<SYS>> for system messages.
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos &&
    src.find("<<SYS>>") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

**Placement**: After line 1644 (`return common_chat_params_init_ministral_3(tmpl, params);`), before line 1646 (`// GPT-OSS ...`).

**Why this is safe**:
- Ministral 3 check (lines 1640–1644) requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` → no overlap.
- GPT-OSS check requires `<|channel|>` → no overlap.
- Llama 2 templates are excluded by `<<SYS>>` guard.
- No existing handler uses `[INST]` without `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]` or `<<SYS>>`.

---

## Exact Edit Points in `common/chat.cpp`

| Location | What to add |
|----------|-------------|
| **Before line 1624** (`static json common_chat_extra_context()`) | Full `common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3` function |
| **After line 1644** (end of Ministral 3 `if` block) | New `if` detection block for Mistral Instruct v3 |

---

## Constraints Satisfied

- ✅ No changes to `src/llama-chat.h` (header file)
- ✅ No changes to any existing handler functions
- ✅ No changes to `src/llama-chat.cpp` (legacy system)
- ✅ Only new code added to `common/chat.cpp`

---

## Verification

1. **Compile**: `cmake --build build` — should compile cleanly with no new warnings.
2. **Basic format test**: Run with the Mistral Nemo model GGUF and a conversation with a system message + user turn; verify the prompt contains `[INST]{system}\n\n{user}[/INST]` and assistant response ends with `</s>`.
3. **Detection log**: With `--log-level debug`, confirm the log line `"Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v3"` appears.
4. **No regression**: Verify the Ministral 3 model still selects the Ministral 3 handler (log line `"Using specialized template: Ministral/Magistral Large 3"`).
5. **Template override**: Pass `--chat-template mistral-v3` or `--chat-template mistral-v3-tekken` and verify the specialized handler is correctly triggered (the override provides the Jinja source which will be pattern-matched).
6. **Run existing tests**: `./build/bin/test-chat-template` and `./build/bin/test-chat` to confirm no regressions.

